[ ] CLI query output is a terminal-aware projection $The CLI query path is a thin projection over graphd. Terminal stdout renders a human table or tree; a pipe emits ndjson for composability; an explicit jsonld flag passes graphd semantic document straight through. Explicit format flags always override terminal-versus-pipe detection. The CLI never parses graph formats and holds no sparql or prefixes.$ !2 #019f76ca-f3b1-7613-a0de-74f453f8576c
[ ] graphd becomes a standalone tool $Make graphd usable directly by humans and agents, not just the CLI. It self-discovers config via core instead of receiving it in the request envelope, owns the named-query registry (move the sparql files in), and owns output modes (rows, ndjson, jsonld) behind a clean argument interface. The CLI then consumes this same public interface, not a private protocol. Someone can install graphd without the CLI. Drop the config field from the stdin request once self-discovery lands.$ !2 #019f76cb-c2f7-7741-9153-1312f4d15d33
[ ] Rescope query output spec to graphd semantic contract $Query output specification was written when the graph lived in core, so it claimed one payload for every consumer. Now that graphd is a separate engine, the spec governs graphd semantic jsonld output and the federation contract, while CLI presentation (terminal table, ndjson pipe) is a client concern documented separately. The meaning-travels-with-the-data principle still holds for the semantic layer.$ !3 #019f77b2-d6d0-7193-acb8-3c54563cf27c
